ited Kingdom"},"nl":{"1145–about 1174":"1145–circa 1174","1136–Male":"1136–Overleden","1141–Male":"1141–Overleden","1143–Male":"1143–Overleden","1145–1174":"1145–1174","1147–Male":"1147–Overleden","1149–Male":"1149–Overleden","1150–Male":"1150–Overleden","1151–Male":"1151–Overleden","1153–Male":"1153–Overleden","–1271":"–1271","1149–Female":"1149–Overleden","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1090–1176":"1090–1176","1113–1185":"1113–1185","1090":"1090","1176":"1176","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1141":"1141","1151":"1151","1271":"1271","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1136":"1136","1113":"1113","1145":"1145","1233":"1233","ABT 1170":"circa 1170","about 1174":"circa 1174","Wickham, Suffolk, England":"Wickham, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1145–about 1174":"1145–about 1174","1136–Male":"1136–Deceased","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1143–Male":"1143–Deceased","1145–1174":"1145–1174","1147–Male":"1147–Deceased","1149–Male":"1149–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","1151–Male":"1151–Deceased","1153–Male":"1153–Deceased","–1271":"–1271","1149–Female":"1149–Deceased","1170–1233":"1170–1233","1090–1176":"1090–1176","1113–1185":"1113–1185","1090":"1090","1176":"1176","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1185":"1185","1174":"1174","1141":"1141","1151":"1151","1271":"1271","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1149":"1149","1147":"1147","1136":"1136","1113":"1113","1145":"1145","1233":"1233","ABT 1170":"about 1170","about 1174":"about 1174","Wickham, Suffolk, England":"Wickham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Sackville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Sauqueville (Seine-Maritime) or Sacquenville (Eure)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sackfield","meanings":["English:  see  Sackville  ."]},{"name":"Sackwild","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a Yiddish form  <i>sakwild</i>, apparently meaning something like ‘game(bird), or venison, in a bag’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When George Sackville was born in 1145, in Wickham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jordan de Saukeville, was 55 and his mother, Clemence de Vere, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Constantia Brooke. He died about 1174, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1145–about 1174":"1145–umbes 1174","1136–Male":"1136–Surnud","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1143–Male":"1143–Surnud","1145–1174":"1145–1174","1147–Male":"1147–Surn